Assessing injury on GOM cetaceans

Preamble

This will be a general preable common to all the documents included as Electronic Supplements to CARMMHA’s offshore injury paper. The exact preamble will be finalized at the time of submission to reflect the submission date and final title, structure, authors etc.

This is an Electronic Supplement to the paper submited to MEPS on the ??-??-???? by Marques, T. A., Thomas, L., Booth, C., Garrison, L. P., Rosel, P. E., Mullin, K. D. & L. Schwacke entitled “Quantifying Deepwater Horizon oil spill induced injury on offshore cetaceans”.

The master file with supplementary material is here: Electronic Supplements master file.

Introduction

In this document we present the results of the age structured model implemented for all species/stock in the GOM, in particular regarding the injury metrics considered:

The three specific injury metrics originally considered in Schwacke et al. (2017) were estimated: (1) lost cetacean years (LCY), the difference between the baseline and injured population sizes, summed over the entire modeled time period; (2) years to recovery (YTR), the number of years required before the injured population trajectory reaches 95% of the baseline population trajectory; and (3) maximum proportional decrease (MPD), the difference between the 2 population trajectories when the injured trajectory is at its lowest point, divided by the baseline. Note that LCY is intuitively the metric that is most dependent on initial population size.

Running the simulations

The code below runs the simulations for all species, and stores the results in appropriate files, stored in appropriate species specific folders. The code below is for completeness only, and IS NOT, AND SHOULD NOT BE, run when this dynamic report is produced.

#define the species we run simulations for
Sps <- c("Bwsp", "Fatt", "Ggri", "Gmac", "Kosp", "Pele", "Pmac", "Satt", "Sbre", "Scly", "Scoe", "Sfro", "Slon", "Ttro", "Ttrs","Ttru")
#define the number of iterations to run
ns <- 1000
# define the number of years each iteration is run for
ny <- 100
#this runs all the simulations and produces outputs for all species
#this code chuck is a separate file: "RunAllSims.R"
# that is the file that should be sourced to run the code
# this code is therefore here just for completeness
# DON NOT turn the "eval=FALSE" into "eval=TRUE"
# unless you are willing to wait for many (many!) hours 
# (or even days, depending on the "ns" you choose)
# for yyour dynamic report to compile
source("Functions/reqfuns.R")         # most functions are here
source("Functions/SilerFuns.R")       # Siler model functions are here
source("Functions/runSims.R")         # To run the simulations for all species
for (i in Sps){
runSims(Sp = i, nsims = ns, nyears = ny)
}
source("Functions/reqfuns.R")         # most functions are here
# Set up a table to hold summary statistics by species
sumres <- data.frame(Sp=Sps, No=NA, peo=NA, LCYo=NA, MPDo=NA, YTRo=NA, Nstart=NA, Nexp=NA, Pexp=NA, LCY=NA, MPD=NA, YTR=NA,  LCYmed=NA, MPDmed=NA, YTRmed=NA)
# Injury metrics and respective 95% quantile-method CI's 
injuryCI <- data.frame(Sp=Sps, LCYmed = NA, LCYl = NA, LCYu = NA, MPDmed = NA, MPDl = NA, MPDu = NA, YTRmed = NA, YTRl = NA, YTRu = NA)
# Some relevant inputs (gd gestation duration and sr survival reduction)
inputs <- data.frame(Sp=Sps, gd = NA, sr = NA)

The species/taxonomic units and the corresponding codes considered in this document are:

  • Ttru bottlenose dolphins BB Tursiops truncatus
  • Pmac sperm whale Physeter macrocephalus
  • Kosp kogia Kogia sp.
  • Scly Clymene dolphin Stenella clymene
  • Pele melon-headed whale Peponocephala electra
  • Ttro offshore bottlenose dolphins Tursiops truncatus
  • Gmac short-finned pilot whale Globicephala macrorhynchus
  • Fatt pygmy killer whale Feresa attenuata
  • Ggri Risso’s dolphin Grampus griseus
  • Sbre rough-toothed dolphin Steno bredanensis
  • Satt pantropical spotted dolphin Stenella attenuata
  • Ttrs shelf bottlenose dolphins Tursiops truncatus
  • Slon spinner dolphin Stenella longirostris
  • Scoe striped dolphin Stenella coeruleoalba
  • Sfro Atlantic spotted dolphin Stenella frontalis
  • Bwsp beaked whales Beaked whales spp

Ttru, bottlenose dolphins in Barataria Bay, are not considered in the offshore paper, but dealt with in a separate paper by Schwacke et al. 

We explicitly re-order the results tables upfront so that results are organized by alphabetical order of the 4 letter code used to describe the taxonomic unit (this is also the order that the species are reported in tables 1 to 3 of the offshore paper).

# note there is no effect if Sps is already in alphabetical order
# but it's here to make sure that this code will work even if
# the vectors Sps is changed
injuryCI <- injuryCI[order(Sps),]
sumres <- sumres[order(Sps),]
inputs <- inputs[order(Sps),]

Note that the initial population sizes and proportion exposed shown below are after removing the very rare instances where the population size would be considered too large to be reasonable. This is imported from a “txt” file produced inside “IniPopSizes.Rmd”. See “IniPopSizes.Rmd” and main paper for details on this choice.

IniPopSizes <- read.table(file = "Table4GetInjury.txt",header=TRUE)
IniPopSizes <- IniPopSizes[order(Sps),]

Results by species

Bottlenose dolphins BB Tursiops truncatus

Note that, while we present here results for Barataria Bay botlenose dolphins, this taxonomic unit is not considered in the offshore paper. They are the subject of a separate dedicated paper by Schwacke et al.

Sp <- "Ttru"
SpInfo <- getSpData(Sp)
## Loading required package: readxl
load(file=paste0("InOutBySp/", SpInfo$folder, "/", Sp, "simres", ns, ".RData"))
inputs$gd[inputs$Sp==Sp] <- SpInfo$gd
inputs$sr[inputs$Sp==Sp] <- with(SpInfo, mean(rbeta(10000, sra, srb)*(sru-srl)+srl))

Population trajectories

plotSims(simres)

Injury measures

x <- getInjury(simres)

colMeans(injury)
##         LCY         YTR         MPD 
## 31896.67702    32.59100    45.18495
apply(injury, 2, median)
##         LCY         YTR         MPD 
## 28387.13477    32.00000    45.88817

Colect information to summary table

sumres[sumres$Sp==Sp, 2:15]<-c(SpInfo$N, SpInfo$pe, SpInfo$LCY, SpInfo$MPD, SpInfo$YTR, IniPopSizes$N[IniPopSizes$Sp==Sp], IniPopSizes$Ne[IniPopSizes$Sp==Sp], IniPopSizes$Pe[IniPopSizes$Sp==Sp], mean(injury$LCY), mean(injury$MPD), mean(injury$YTR),  median(injury$LCY), median(injury$MPD), median(injury$YTR))

and collect information to injury summary table

injuryCI[injuryCI$Sp==Sp, 2:10]<-c(median(injury$LCY), quantile(injury$LCY, probs=c(0.025,0.975)), median(injury$MPD), quantile(injury$MPD, probs = c(0.025, 0.975)), median(injury$YTR), quantile(injury$YTR,probs = c(0.025, 0.975)))

As noted above, one can anticipate that LCY would be strongly dependent on the initial population size and the proportion exposed. Therefore, we fit a linear model to explain LCY as a function of these two quantities. The summary of the corresponding linear model follows. Then we present a plot representing the observed values of LCY and those obtained by predicting from fitting a linear model of LCY as explained by initial population size and the proportion exposed.

We note that, when compared to the earlier assessments, the injury seems now considerably less than before. A large part of this was a bug in the calculation in the MMIQT values for LCY, but a part of it might be due to the modelling, and the many changes implemented from then to now.

Until almost the last minute, when we were considering the decrease in the survival probability as before, the results for BND in BB were similar to those obtained before. However, after receiving the preliminary results from the SECR model implemented by Richard Glennie that we are hoping to use, it became apparent that the impact was much lower, essentially because the initial drop survival is estimated not to have been as strong as it was assumed before.

Species by species discussion

Here we compare the results for each of the species with those obtained before, trying to shed light on what the differences found might be due to.

To do so we show again the before and after key values for each species.

Bwsp beaked whales Beaked whales spp

We observe the following changes in injury and in key quantities that might affect the injury (initial population size and the proportion of the population exposed):

  • lost cetacean years came down from 7838 to 1319
  • maximum proportional decrease came down from -0.06 to -0.04
  • years to recovery came down from 10 to 1.8
  • The assumed initial population size changed from 1167 to 3098
  • The proportion of the population exposed before was 0.119 and it is now 0.14.

Fatt pygmy killer whale Feresa attenuata

We observe the following changes in injury and in key quantities that might affect the injury (initial population size and the proportion of the population exposed):

  • lost cetacean years came down from 2501 to 1281
  • maximum proportional decrease came down from -0.07 to -0.044
  • years to recovery came down from 29 to 2.8
  • The assumed initial population size changed from 1696 to 2152
  • The proportion of the population exposed before was 0.15 and it is now 0.145.

Ggri Risso’s dolphin Grampus griseus

We observe the following changes in injury and in key quantities that might affect the injury (initial population size and the proportion of the population exposed):

  • lost cetacean years came down from 6258 to 2482
  • maximum proportional decrease came down from -0.03 to -0.06
  • years to recovery came down from NA to 8
  • The assumed initial population size changed from 1848 to 3063
  • The proportion of the population exposed before was 0.076 and it is now 0.197.

Gmac short-finned pilot whale Globicephala macrorhynchus

We observe the following changes in injury and in key quantities that might affect the injury (initial population size and the proportion of the population exposed):

  • lost cetacean years came down from 5304 to 1090
  • maximum proportional decrease came down from -0.03 to -0.037
  • years to recovery came down from NA to 1.6
  • The assumed initial population size changed from 1641 to 2065
  • The proportion of the population exposed before was 0.057 and it is now 0.12.

Kosp kogia Kogia sp.

We observe the following changes in injury and in key quantities that might affect the injury (initial population size and the proportion of the population exposed):

  • lost cetacean years came down from 49100 to 1451
  • maximum proportional decrease came down from -0.06 to -0.055
  • years to recovery came down from 11 to 5.5
  • The assumed initial population size changed from 6690 to 2322
  • The proportion of the population exposed before was 0.151 and it is now 0.197.

Pele melon-headed whale Peponocephala electra

We observe the following changes in injury and in key quantities that might affect the injury (initial population size and the proportion of the population exposed):

  • lost cetacean years came down from 14887 to 3068
  • maximum proportional decrease came down from -0.07 to -0.044
  • years to recovery came down from 29 to 2.5
  • The assumed initial population size changed from 1696 to 5784
  • The proportion of the population exposed before was 0.15 and it is now 0.152.

Pmac sperm whale Physeter macrocephalus

We observe the following changes in injury and in key quantities that might affect the injury (initial population size and the proportion of the population exposed):

  • lost cetacean years came down from 13197 to 2555
  • maximum proportional decrease came down from -0.07 to -0.066
  • years to recovery came down from 21 to 10.4
  • The assumed initial population size changed from 1616 to 2561
  • The proportion of the population exposed before was 0.161 and it is now 0.191.

For Pmac the the lost cetacean years came down from 13197 to 2555, but in fact the true value bug apart was 5637 (cf. GOMOSES 2020 poster). Therefore we would expect a decrease of the LCY by more than 50% just due to the bug (in the specific case of the sperm whale: 57.286 %).

Satt pantropical spotted dolphin Stenella attenuata

We observe the following changes in injury and in key quantities that might affect the injury (initial population size and the proportion of the population exposed):

  • lost cetacean years came down from 363780 to 33874
  • maximum proportional decrease came down from -0.09 to -0.037
  • years to recovery came down from 39 to 0.9
  • The assumed initial population size changed from 33382 to 81233
  • The proportion of the population exposed before was 0.196 and it is now 0.155.

We note that the assumed initial population size increased considerably compared to the MMIQT, which per se would lead to an increase in LCY, everything else being the same (NA to ).

While a drop in the LCY can be explained by the already mentioned bug in the LCY calculation, and the reduction in the proportion exposed is also relevant (before it was 0.196, now it is 0.155, these do not seem enough to justify the observed differences, namely in the YTR.

Sbre rough-toothed dolphin Steno bredanensis

We observe the following changes in injury and in key quantities that might affect the injury (initial population size and the proportion of the population exposed):

  • lost cetacean years came down from 50464 to 2489
  • maximum proportional decrease came down from -0.17 to -0.042
  • years to recovery came down from 54 to 2.1
  • The assumed initial population size changed from 2414 to 4867
  • The proportion of the population exposed before was 0.409 and it is now 0.148.

The major difference observed for the proportion exposed could explain most of the diferences.
